Bombard in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of the main assets of American President Barack Obama.
It seems today, however, that his remarks have trapped him in a dilemma.
After having stated last March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and having mentioned last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama would lose face if he does not respond strongly to the killing, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1,000 civilians using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get so entrenched in such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry is right to characterize the use of gas as "moral obscenity."
But torturing children, a precursor to the civil war two years ago, is just as much.
And is it morally more obscene to kill civilians with chemical weapons than to bomb them, shoot at them, or let them starve?
It is commonly accepted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Mass destruction weapons, particularly the nuclear bomb, certainly cause more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing about 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
A viewpoint, notably advocated by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, suggests that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to abandon the use of chemical weapons and return to "more conventional means of massacring his people."
In my opinion, this makes no sense.
The question is surely that of the massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral outrage, justified as it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sensible person has suggested that a military intervention in China would be a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is this therefore a legal issue? The use of chemical weapons constitutes, as a matter of fact, a violation of international conventions, including the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, to which Syria is a party.
Therefore, there are valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he must be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), which, by the way, was established by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not a policy easily defensible.
One could nevertheless argue that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn away when innocent people are being massacred?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should the line be drawn?
How many murders constitute genocide?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Or is the number not taken into account?
After all, genocide is a matter of intent; there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons - or even two - would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to consider before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance of improving the situation, saving lives, and making the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Answering it involves asking oneself: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the actions of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" is more likely to produce results in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a major power.
No one would consider missile strikes against China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or to enforce international norms and conventions regarding war.
As many have pointed out, Syria is not Libya or Mali.
She is not a great power either.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving larger countries, including Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
There is no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is by no means certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a broader conflict.
In fact, some advocates of American intervention—both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks"—seem to desire the opposite: they are calling for a war with Iran.
And Obama probably established a connection in his mind between the red line regarding Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, in order to prevent Iran from developing nuclear weapons.
What, then, should one expect from American strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that their purpose is not to bring down the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile would be enough to make the United States a direct participant in this war, causing a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly wise.
This viewpoint is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
It is the opinion of most Europeans.
And a majority of Americans.
It might even be Obama's view, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time by delegating to the American Congress the authorization for the use of military force in Syria.
Since taking office, her relations with Congress have been anything but easy.
But he needs it more than ever today to cover his back.
